      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and the principal isnt going down as much as i thought it would even though i pay the same amount every month. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated on a declining balance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The interest on your student loan is likely calculated using a method called the \"declining balance\" method, which can be a bit tricky to understand. It's a bit like a game of \"keep away\" with the interest, where the lender keeps adding interest to the principal, but the borrower is trying to pay down the principal. Think of it like a never-ending battle between the borrower and the lender, with the borrower trying to chip away at the principal and the lender trying to keep it from decreasing. \n\nIn this method, the interest is calculated as a percentage of the current outstanding balance, not just the original loan amount. So, if you have a $10,000 loan with a 6% interest rate, and you make a payment, the interest for that month might be calculated as 6% of the new balance, not the original $10,000. This means that if you pay $100, the interest might be $60 (6% of the new balance), leaving you with $40 to apply to the principal. \n\nAs you continue making payments, the principal will decrease, but the interest will still be calculated based on the new balance. This can create a bit of a snowball effect, where the interest",
